Genome.Name: Wolbachia endosymbiont of Drosophila melanogaster strain wMel
Host.Name: Fruit fly, Drosophila melanogaster
Sequencing.Centers: TIGR
Comments: Wolbachia endosymbiont of Drosophila melanogaster. Wolbachia endosymbiont of Drosophila melanogaster, also known as Wolbachia pipentis strain wMel, naturally infects Drosophila melanogaster and is a member of supergroup A. The genome contains a large number of repetitive elements as well as proteins with ankyrin repeats that may be important in bacterium-host interactions. The chromosome also contains genes that encode a type IV secretion system.

Genome.Name: Wolbachia endosymbiont of Drosophila ananassae
Host.Name: Fruit fly, Drosophila ananassae
Sequencing.Centers: TIGR
Comments: Wolbachia endosymbiont of Drosophila ananassae. This strain has a low CIQ (Cytoplasmic Incompatibility Quotient), which leads to a decreased egg mortality in the infected host strain. This sequence was pulled from a Drosophila ananassae genome sequencing project. Sequences represented as part of this project do not match any known Drosophila sequence. The wAna genome is at approximately 8X coverage and that 98% of the genome had been recovered. This is the first instance of the recovery of near-complete genomes of endosymbiotic organisms from a eukaryotic genome sequencing project.

Genome.Name: Wolbachia endosymbiont of Drosophila simulans
Host.Name: Drosophila simulans
Sequencing.Centers: TIGR
Comments: Wolbachia  endosymbiont of Drosophila simulans. This strain contains a bacteriophage which undergoes lateral transfers between Wolbachia in different insect hosts. This bacteria can form spore-like structures in Drosophila simulans but not in Drosophila melanogaster.  This sequence was pulled from a Drosophila simulans genome sequencing project. Sequences represented as part of this project do not match any known Drosophila sequence. The wSim was estimated at 2X coverage, with 65-80% of the genome. This is the first instance of the recovery of near-complete genomes of endosymbiotic organisms from a eukaryotic genome sequencing project.;low contig N50

Genome.Name: Wolbachia pipientis wMelPop
Host.Name: Fruit fly, Drosophila melanogaster
Sequencing.Centers: Monash University
Comments: The endosymbiotic bacterium Wolbachia pipientis typically has only mildly beneficial or mildy deleterious effects on its hosts. The strain wMelPop, however, over-replicates in its host, leading to pathogenesis and early host death. We have sequenced the genome of wMelPop and compared it to the genome of the closely related, non-pathogenic strain wMel.

Host.Name: Tsetse fly, Glossina morsitans morsitans

Comments: The draft genome of the Wolbachia strain present in Glossina morsitans morsitans is presented. It is most similar with the two Wolbachia strains associated with Drosophila melanogaster and D. simulans.

Genome.Name: Wolbachia pipientis strain wRec
Host.Name: Fruit fly, Drosophila recens
Sequencing.Centers: Vanderbilt University
Comments: wRec, a Wolbachia pipientis strain inhabiting the mushroom-feeding fly Drosophila recens, was sequenced along with some of its insect host DNA. wRec is a multipotent strain of Wolbachia that can cause multiple phenotypes of reproductive manipulation depending on its host (cytoplasmic incompatibility or male killing). PCR screens have previously indicated that wRec lacks prophage WO, a dsDNA virus that is nearly universal in arthropod Wolbachia, and which has been hypothesized to be involved these reproductive manipulations. Since cytoplasmic incompatibility is being used as a driver of Wolbachia infection in wild mosquito populations, blocking vector competence for diseases such as dengue and malaria, its mechanisms of action are of particular interest. We sequenced this Wolbachia strain to investigate the missing phage anomaly and to seek clues for the causative factors of Wolbachia-induced reproductive manipulations.

Genome.Name: Wolbachia strain wAu
Sequencing.Centers: SC
Comments: Wolbachia intracellular bacteria manipulate the reproduction of their arthropod hosts, including inducing sterility between populations known as cytoplasmic incompatibility. Certain strains have been identified that are unable to induce or rescue CI, including wAu from Drosophila. Genome sequencing and comparison with CI-inducing related strain wMel was undertaken in order to better understand the molecular basis of the phenotype.

Genome.Name: Wolbachia endosymbiont of Drosophila ananassae strain wAna_India
Host.Name: Drosophila ananassae 14024-0371.31
Sequencing.Centers: University of Maryland Baltimore
Comments: The Wolbachia endosymbiont from three geographically distinct strains of Drosophila ananassae were sequenced. Since the Hawaii strain of D. ananassae is known to have a Wolbachia lateral gene transfer (Hotopp, J. D. et al., 2007), the Wolbachia cells were transfected and cultured in Sua5B cells. The India and Indonesia strains of D. ananassae are not thought to have a Wolbachia lateral gene transfer.

Genome.Name: Wolbachia pipientis wBol1-b
Host.Name: Common eggfly, Hypolimnas bolina
Sequencing.Centers: UQ
Comments: The endosymbiont Wolbachia pipientis causes diverse and sometimes dramatic phenotypes in its invertebrate hosts. We have sequenced the genome of the strain wBol1-b, found in the butterfly Hypolimnas bolina, which kills the male offspring of infected hosts during embyronic development and is closely related to the non-male-killing strain wPip from Culex pipiens. The results of this project will provide a useful resource for future investigations of the genetic bases of male killing in Wolbachia, and further our understanding of the role played in Wolbachia genome evolution by frequent horizontal gene transfer.  This is the first Wolbachia genome project to be completed using a combination of a novel method for preparing sequencing material and next-generation sequencing techniques. Because the ratio of Wolbachia to host DNA is typically very low, previous Wolbachia genome projects have required extensive and laborious purifications from extremely large numbers of host individuals before sequencing. Here we have overcome this difficulty by using a short period of cell culture to amplify Wolbachia originally isolated from a single host individual and employing a simple and rapid purification method to obtain exceptionally pure endosymbiont material for sequencing.

Genome.Name: Wolbachia endosymbiont of Onchocerca volvulus str. Cameroon
Sequencing.Centers: SC
Comments: Despite their importance globally, both medically and economically, parasitic helminth (worm) research has remained relatively untouched by genomics. Worm infections account for morbidity equivalent to more than 100 million disability adjusted life years from more than one billion infections globally. The 50 Helminth Genomes Initiative is collaborative project that aims to survey the genomes of nematodes and platyhelminths that are either of medical or veterinary importance, or as used as models for those. It will include all the neglected metazoan parasites. Preliminary illumina sequencing from these helminth species will be used to produce draft genomic assemblies which will create a unique genomic resource. Draft assemblies of the genomes will underpin research and progress into these neglected diseases. Gene and protein predictions will provide a resource that can be mined by researchers for diagnostic markers, new drug targets or vaccines. Comparing the genomes will yield evolutionary insights and will enable more to be learnt about the genomic basis for the huge differences in the biology of these parasites and the diseases they cause.

Genome.Name: Wolbachia endosymbiont of Cimex lectularius wCle
Host.Name: Cimex lectularius JESC
Sequencing.Centers: The Open University of Japan
Comments: Transition from parasitism to mutualism must have occurred in diverse symbiotic associations, whose mechanism is of evolutionary interest. Wolbachia endosymbionts are ubiquitously found among insects, and generally regarded as their facultative and parasitic associates. In the bedbug Cimex lectularius, however, a Wolbachia strain wCle provides the host with B vitamins deficient in blood meal, thereby establishing an obligate nutritional mutualism.

Host.Name: Scale insect, Dactylopius coccus
Sequencing.Centers: Universidad Nacional Autonoma de Mexico
Comments: The cochineal insect Dactylopius coccus is the source of the carminic acid dye used worldwide. The microbiome of D. coccus has been poorly studied. Using a metagenomic approach, the Wolbachia strain wDacB, belonging to supergroup B, was identified among the microbiota inhabiting D. coccus in Mexico. The genome sequence of wDacB was sequenced and analyzed.
